 a range of works, from nineteenth-century American literature to contemporary queer of color art and writing by contemporary American artists including Wilmer Wilson IV, Tourmaline, Tony Kushner, Junot Díaz, Glenn Ligon, Toshi Reagon, and Sharon Hayes. Throughout, escape emerges as a story not of individuality but of collectivity and entanglement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican American arts2DLC. 0aAfrican American arts. 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aEscape (Psychology)zUnited States2DLC. 0aEscape (Psychology)zUnited States. 0aEscape (Psychology). 0aEscape in literature2DLC. 0aEscape in literature. 0aPerforming artsxSocial aspectszUnited States2DLC. 0aPerforming artsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aQueer theory2DLC. 0aQueer theory. 0aRace in literature2DLC. 0aRace in literature. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059271?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059271423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059271/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles